@database TTX_Help_SASC.guide
@$VER: TTX_Help_SASC.guide 2.2 (23.10.94)
@author Ken Yarnall

@node Main "Help on the SAS/C++ interface"

	@{b}TTX to SAS/C Interface Manual 2.2 (23-Oct-94)@{ub}

	Written by Ken Yarnall (kyarnall@bix.com)

	@{" Installation " link "Installation"}
	@{" SAS/C Menu   " link "SAS Menu"}
	@{" SCMsg Menu   " link "SCMsg Menu"}

@endnode

@node "Installation"

@{b}Usage requirements@{ub}

This version of TTX<->SASC @{b}requires@{ub} version 6.50 or greater of the SAS/C++©
Development System.


@{b}Files@{ub}

Most of the files belong in the TurboText: tree, and thus will come
pre-installed for you.  The only file you need to move is
@{" TurboText:Rexx/TTX_SASC/sc/SCMSG " link "TurboText:Rexx/TTX_SASC/sc/SCMSG/Main"}, which belongs in @{b}both@{ub} ENVARC:sc/ and
ENV:sc/.  Click @{" Here " system "copy QUIET CLONE TurboText:Rexx/TTX_SASC/sc/SCMSG TO ENVARC:SC/SCMSG"} to move this file to ENVARC:SC now (a reboot will
then be needed), or do it by hand.


@{b}TurboText definitions@{ub}

To install the @{" SAS/C Menus " link "Main"} under TurboText, do one of the following:

1) Choose @{b}Prefs/Open Definitionss...@{ub}, and select @{" TTX_Interface_SASC.dfn " link "TurboText:Support/TTX_Interface_SASC.dfn/Main"} in the
file requester.  The two menus that control the SAS/C compiler should
appear in TurboText's menu strip.

2) To make this a permanent addition to your system, insert the lines

	@{b}LINKS:
	  TurboText:Support/TTX_Interface_SASC.dfn
	#@{ub}

to your TTX_Startup.dfn file.


@{b}SCMsgź message browser@{ub}

To use the message browser, remember that you must set the "ErrorRexx"
option of the SAS/C++© compiler.

@endnode

@node "SAS Menu"
@title "SAS/C Menu"

	@{" Make Project... ^F6 " link "Make Project"}
	@{" Compile File... ^F7 " link "Compile File"}
	@{" Options           » " link "Options"}
	@{" Debug Program     » " link "Debug Program"}

	@{" Help              » " link "Help"}

@endnode


@node "SCMsg Menu"

	@{" Start Browser    " link "Browser Commands"}
	@{" Show Browser     " link "Browser Commands"}
	@{" Hide Browser     " link "Browser Commands"}
	@{" Clear Browser    " link "Browser Commands"}

	@{" Current          " link "Navigation"}
	@{" Previous     ^F9 " link "Navigation"}
	@{" Next        ^F10 " link "Navigation"}
	@{" First            " link "Navigation"}
	@{" Last             " link "Navigation"}
	@{" Delete           " link "Navigation"}

@endnode

@node "Make Project"

Invokes SCMsgź on the current file.  This will start SCMsgź if it is not
running, set the environment variable @{b}ENV:sc/projdir@{ub} to point to the
current directory, and send SCMsgź the build command.  You may then use the
@{" Navigation commands " link "Navigation"} to investigate any errors that SCMsgź reports.

@endnode

@node "Compile File"

Compiles the current file via sc (not SCMsgź) using an "on-the-fly" shell
script.  It also starts SCMsgź, if it isn't running, for error reporting.
You may then use the @{" Navigation commands " link "Navigation"} to investigate any errors that
SCMsgź reports.

@endnode

@node "Options"

@{b}Options Submenu@{ub}

	@{" General...  ^F8 " link "Options-General"}
	@{" Link On         " link "Options-Link On|Off"}
	@{" Link Off        " link "Options-Link On|Off"}

@endnode

@node "Options-General"

Options » General... invokes SCOptsź on the current directory, allowing
you to set any compile/link options for SAS/C that you wish.

@endnode

@node "Options-Link On|Off"

These two selections allow you to turn linking on and off.  By looking at
how these are done in the @{" TTX_Interface_SASC.dfn " link "TurboText:Support/TTX_Interface_SASC.dfn/Main"} file, you can easily
extend the Options Submenu to include such quick access to whatever options
you want.

@endnode

@node "Debug Program"

The two entries in this submenu, @{b}CLI@{ub} and @{b}WB@{ub}, start CPRź with the
corresponding startup option.  It is assumed that the program to be
debugged had the same name as the current file, with the extension (.c,
.cpp, etc.) stripped off.

@endnode

@node "Help"

    @{" SAS/C On-line Help " link "SAS Help"}
    @{" SAS/C Menus Help   " link "Menus Help"}

@endnode

@node "SAS Help"

Brings up the SAS/C++© On-line AmigaGuide© reference manual.  This opens
the title page of that document, allowing you to access the entire SAS/C++©
help system.

@endnode

@node "Menus Help"

Bring up this document.

@endnode


@node "Browser Commands"

@{b}Start Browser@{ub}
@{b}Show Browser @{ub}
@{b}Hide Browser @{ub}
@{b}Clear Browser@{ub}

These commands start, show (if hidden), hide, and clear the SCMsgź error
message browser.

@endnode

@node "Navigation"

@{b}Current@{ub}
@{b}Previous@{ub}
@{b}Next@{ub}
@{b}First@{ub}
@{b}Last@{ub}
@{b}Delete@{ub}

These commands allow you to move around in the message browser, while you
are editing in TurboText.  As you move about in the browser, the current
error message is also displayed by TurboText (opening new windows if
necessary).  @{b}Delete@{ub} removes the current message from the list.

It is also possible to move to a particular error by double clicking on
that error in the SCMsgź window.

@endnode
